  "topic": "What is stereotype threat in STEM? Should we address it? And how?",
  "opinion": "As a 65-year-old hairdresser in Kansas City, I've spent my life working with people from all walks of life, and I've seen firsthand how stereotypes can hold folks back, even if I'm not directly in the STEM fields myself. Stereotype threat, from what I understand, is when someone feels anxious or under pressure because they're worried about confirming a negative stereotype about their group—like women or minorities being told they're not good at math or science. It's like when a customer comes into my shop feeling nervous about a new haircut because they've heard people with their hair type can't pull it off; that fear can make them tense up and not enjoy the experience, or even avoid trying something new altogether. In STEM, this threat can make talented people doubt themselves, perform worse on tests, or even leave these fields entirely, which seems a real shame because we need all kinds of minds to solve problems and innovate. I believe we should definitely address it, not just because it's unfair, but because it's wasteful—we're missing out on potential scientists and engineers who could help our communities. How to address it? Well, in my line of work, I've learned that a little encouragement goes a long way. In STEM, that might mean creating more supportive environments where everyone feels welcome, like having mentors who understand these pressures or highlighting diverse role models in science and math. Schools and workplaces could focus on individual growth rather than comparing people to stereotypes, much like I tailor haircuts to each person's unique style instead of assuming based on appearance. Also, raising awareness about stereotype threat itself can help, so people recognize it and don't let it define them. It's about building confidence and opportunity, something I've seen work wonders with my clients over the years. By tackling this, we can open doors for more people to contribute their talents, making STEM stronger and more inclusive 